This report documents the complete design, implementation, and analysis of a \textbf{scientific calculator} built on the \textbf{ATmega328P microcontroller} (Arduino UNO). The central challenge is the absence of a hardware Floating Point Unit (FPU) on 8-bit AVR microcontrollers, which makes computing transcendental functions ($\sin x$, $\ln x$, $e^x$, etc.) expensive and inaccurate via standard libraries.

The solution reformulates each mathematical function as an \textbf{Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE)} and solves it using the \textbf{Runge-Kutta 4\textsuperscript{th} Order (RK4)} method. A comparative benchmark of five numerical methods confirms that RK4 achieves maximum accuracy at the 32-bit precision floor while consuming only \textbf{12.3 KB Flash} and \textbf{350 bytes SRAM}.

User input is handled through a \textbf{5$\times$5 push-button matrix} via row-column scanning. Expressions are parsed with the \textbf{Shunting Yard algorithm} and evaluated in Reverse Polish Notation (RPN). A bug in multi-digit expression tokenisation was identified, root-caused, and fixed in \texttt{pars.c}, \texttt{keypad.c}, and \texttt{main.c}.

\medskip\noindent
\textbf{Keywords:} Scientific Calculator, ATmega328P, Runge-Kutta, Numerical Methods, Embedded C, Shunting Yard Algorithm, AVR-GCC
\end{mdframed}

