\chapter{Project Overview}
% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\section{Objective}

The goal is to build a \textbf{fully functional scientific calculator} on an \textbf{Arduino UNO} (ATmega328P) \emph{without} relying on pre-built math libraries or hardware floating-point units. Every mathematical function is implemented from first principles using \textbf{numerical methods} derived from ODE models.

\begin{infobox}[Why Bare-Metal Arithmetic?]
The ATmega328P has \emph{no hardware FPU}. A single \texttt{float} division costs \textbf{505 CPU cycles} --- more than twice an integer division. Standard C library math functions use large lookup tables that eat into the 32 KB Flash. This project demonstrates that a \emph{unified} RK4-based numerical framework achieves hardware-limited precision in just 12.3 KB Flash and 350 B RAM.
\end{infobox}

