\subsection{Scanning Principle}

The Arduino drives each \textbf{row LOW} in turn while reading all \textbf{column pins}. A pressed button pulls its column LOW, uniquely identifying the key as:
\[
\text{Key} = (\text{Active Row},\ \text{Column reading LOW})
\]

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.85,
  btn/.style={draw=PrimaryLight, fill=BgPanel, circle, minimum size=0.72cm, font=\tiny}]
\foreach \c in {0,...,4} {
  \foreach \r in {0,...,2} {
    \node[btn] at (2*\c, -1.6*\r) {};
  }
}
% Row lines
\foreach \r/\lab in {0/Row 1, 1/Row 2, 2/Row 3} {
  \draw[Accent, line width=1.2pt] (-0.7, -1.6*\r) -- (8.7, -1.6*\r);
  \node[left, font=\tiny\bfseries, text=Accent] at (-0.8, -1.6*\r) {\lab};
}
% Column lines
\foreach \c/\lab in {0/C1,1/C2,2/C3,3/C4,4/C5} {
  \draw[Primary, line width=1.2pt] (2*\c, 0.7) -- (2*\c, -3.9);
  \node[above, font=\tiny\bfseries, text=Primary] at (2*\c, 0.75) {\lab};
}
% Pressed button highlight
\node[draw=Accent, fill=Accent!25, circle, minimum size=0.74cm, line width=2pt] at (2,-1.6) {};
\node[font=\tiny\bfseries\color{Accent}] at (2,-1.6) {KEY};
