\section{Accuracy Comparison for $\sin(x)$, $h \approx 0.06$}

Accuracy is measured in \textbf{Units in the Last Place (ULP)} vs.\ the MPFR multi-precision library:
\[
\mathrm{Error}_\mathrm{ULP} = \frac{|y_\mathrm{calc} - y_\mathrm{true}|}{\varepsilon(y_\mathrm{true})}
\]

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{L{3.6cm} C{3.4cm} C{3.0cm} C{2.4cm}}
\rowcolor{PrimaryDark}
\thdcell{Algorithm} & \thdcell{Max Error (ULP)} & \thdcell{RMS Error} & \thdcell{Stability} \\
\altrow \textbf{RK4} & $\mathbf{2.38\times10^{11}}$ & $\mathbf{3.44\times10^{-7}}$ & \textbf{High} \\
Trapezoidal & $6.00\times10^{14}$ & $8.77\times10^{-4}$ & High \\
\altrow Heun (RK2) & $1.20\times10^{15}$ & $1.74\times10^{-3}$ & Moderate \\
Forward Euler & $1.86\times10^{15}$ & $8.56\times10^{-2}$ & Unstable \\
\altrow Backward Euler & $2.84\times10^{15}$ & $7.27\times10^{-2}$ & Unstable \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\begin{infobox}[Precision Floor Insight]
On the ATmega328P, \texttt{avr-gcc} treats \texttt{float} and \texttt{double} as 32-bit IEEE 754. For RK4 the error reaches a \textbf{minimum at $h\approx0.03$}. Smaller $h$ only increases execution time because accumulated rounding error dominates --- making any method of order $>4$ pointless on this platform. RK4 is the optimal choice.
\end{infobox}

\begin{successbox}[Why RK4 Was Selected]
RK4 achieves the \textbf{lowest error} at the hardware precision floor, guarantees \textbf{predictable fixed execution time} (no adaptive stepping), and the entire firmware fits in \textbf{12.3 KB Flash} and \textbf{350 B SRAM} --- comfortable for the ATmega328P.
\end{successbox}

